Decreasing slightly the likelihood of a vaccine before January 2017 based on article at link: This study, using laboratory methods, indicates that prior or co- infection with Dengue virus is likely to enhance Zika virus infection through a process known as antibody-dependent enhancement (ADE) . A similar phenomenon is already known to occur between different strains of dengue virus, a close relative of Zika and results in greater severity of symptoms when it occurs. This means the "wrong" vaccine could enhance severity of Zika infection. Alternatively, as discussed in the article, the possibility also exists to combine Zika and Dengue vaccine in the same preparation to protect against both. http://biorxiv.org/content/early/2016/04/25/050112

Zika virus is a flavivirus like Dengue and Yellow fever. Looking into the history of these two well-known diseases I found that both were discovered and studied many years before a vaccine attempt was performed; Yellow fever: first studies around 1900, then the studies of Theiler on the virus (1930) and subsequent vaccine development (1937) that lead to the first human trial (1938). Dengue: Early efforts to understand the virus dated around 1956, vaccine trial on humans by US Naval Medical Research Center performed in 2006. No approved vaccine developed yet.

DNA sequencing techniques is changing how research labs understand, test, and develop solutions. The essence of the IFP is "start" of phase 1 human trials. Given the new genetic testing options, this phase may be a lot closer than prior times.

Claims and press releases are flying around but the rate-limiting step for vaccine development seems to be the IND application. There's a lot of hype about Zika, but without IND approval, you can't begin Phase I human testing.
http://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/30/business/vaccine-for-zika-virus-may-be-years-away-disease-experts-warn.html
A long way to go at this point.

Pessimistic. General rule of thumb is to take the expected time and multiply it by 2, then add 6 months. Worried about the planning fallacy here and the inability of scientists/media/lay observers to properly budget time for all the given considerations before human trials begin.

yeah, actually I think this is a pretty good bet. There are multiple vaccines in pre-clinical trials - though that says nothing about whether those vaccines will go on to clinical trials, but something seems likely with multiple companies already at that stage.
